Awards||Best Actor||{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.television.co.jp/drama/academy/2012/02/post_781.html|script-title=ja:\u4e3b\u6f14\u7537\u512a\u8cde|date=February 17, 2012|language=Japanese|publisher=Television Drama Academy Awards|accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013||17th Nikkan Sports Drama Grand Prix (Spring)||Best Actor||rowspan=\"3\"|''Kazoku Game''||{{won}}\n|-\n| 77th Television Drama Academy Awards||Best Actor||{{won}}\n|-\n| 2014||23rd Annual TV Life Awards||Best Actor||{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|title=2013\u5e74\u300c\u5e74\u9593\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u5927\u8cde\u300d\u306f\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u4e3b\u6f14\u300e\u5bb6\u65cf\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u300f\u306b\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01|url=http://www.tvlife.jp/2014/02/26/18065|publisher=TV Life|accessdate=February 26, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227050258/http://www.tvlife.jp/2014/02/26/18065|archivedate=February 27, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|group=fn}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|1123941}}\n* {{ann|people|id=56061}}\n\n{{Arashi}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sakurai, Sho}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arashi members]]\n[[Category:Japanese male pop singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese rappers]]\n[[Category:Keio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Japanese male actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese male film actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese male television actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese idols]]\n[[Category:Singers from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name = Sho Sakurai\n| native_name         = \u6afb\u4e95 \u7fd4\n| native_name_lang    = ja\n| image =\n| alt = \n| caption =\n| image_size = \n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = \n| alias = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1982|01|25}}\n| death_date =\n| origin = [[Minato, Tokyo|Minato]], Tokyo, Japan\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[J-pop]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* [[Rapping|rapper]]\n* actor\n* News presenter\n* [[Master of Ceremonies|host]]}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist| \n* Vocals\n* piano}}\n| years_active = 1995\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist| \n* [[Johnny & Associates]]\n* [[J Storm]]}}\n| associated_acts = [[Arashi]]\n| website =\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Sho Sakurai'''|\u6afb\u4e95 \u7fd4|Sakurai Sh\u014d}} (born January 25, 1982) is a Japanese singer, songwriter, [[Rapping|rapper]], actor, News presenter, [[Master of Ceremonies|host]] and former radio host. He is a member of the [[boy band]] [[Arashi]].\n\nSakurai began his career in the entertainment industry when he joined the Japanese talent agency [[Johnny & Associates]] in 1995 at the age of 13. About seven years after his debut as a singer with Arashi in 1999, he became a [[newscaster]] in 2006, appearing in the news program ''News Zero'' every Monday. In 2008, he was appointed the official newscaster for the news coverage of the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games in Beijing]] on [[Nippon Television|NTV]].<ref name=\"beijing\" /> For his work as an actor, singer and newscaster, Sakurai became one of the recipients of [[GQ]] Japan's Men of the Year award in 2009.<ref name=\"GQ\">{{cite web|url=http://career.oricon.co.jp/news/71672/full/|title=\u4eca\u5e74\u6700\u3082\u8f1d\u3044\u305f\u7537\u6027\u306b\u5d50\u30fb\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u7b11\u798f\u4ead\u9db4\u74f6\u3089 \u300eGQ Men of the Year2009\u300f|date=December 16, 2009|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"GQ2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-5589|title=GQ Men of the Year 2009: Sakurai, Shofukutei|date=December 16, 2009|publisher=Tokyograph|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref> His father is Shun Sakurai, former vice-minister of the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-np.co.jp/s/article/2015071701001145.html|title=\u300c\u5d50\u300d\u685c\u4e95\u7fd4\u3055\u3093\u7236\u89aa\u7dcf\u52d9\u6b21\u5b98\u306b\u3000\u65e7\u90f5\u653f\u7701\u51fa\u8eab\u306e\u685c\u4e95\u4fca\u6c0f|work=[[Tokyo Shimbun]]|date=July 17, 2015|accessdate=July 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719020947/http://www.tokyo-np.co.jp/s/article/2015071701001145.html|archivedate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nSakurai was born in [[Maebashi]], [[Gunma Prefecture]], and grew up in [[Minato, Tokyo|Minato]], Tokyo, the oldest of three children.<ref name=pia2009A>{{cite journal|date=August 27, 2009|title=\u305d\u3057\u3066\u50d5\u3089\u306f\u5d50\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305f Arashi Story 1980\u20132009|journal=Pia|pages=10\u201322}}</ref> His father, {{Nihongo|Shun Sakurai|\u685c\u4e95 \u4fca}}, is a former government official.<ref name=japaneseperspective>{{cite web|url=http://japaneseperspective.com/sho-sakurai/|title=Sho Sakurai|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2017|publisher=Japanese Perspective|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602021608/http://japaneseperspective.com/sho-sakurai/|archive-date=June 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sakurai has a younger sister, {{Nihongo|Mai|\u821e}} (b. 1986), who is a journalist for [[Nippon TV]], and a younger brother, {{Nihongo|Shu|\u4fee}} (b. 1994).<ref name=japaneseperspective />\n\nSakurai attended Keio Yochisha Elementary School, an affiliated elementary school of [[Keio University]].<ref name=pia2009B>{{cite journal|date=August 27, 2009|title=\u305d\u3057\u3066\u50d5\u3089\u306f\u5d50\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305f Arashi Story 1980\u20132009|journal=Pia|pages=10\u201322}}</ref> From age three to ten, he did many extracurricular activities, including [[kendo]], swimming, football, [[oil painting]], [[Japanese calligraphy|calligraphy]], and [[scouting]].<ref name=newspost7>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-postseven.com/archives/20120721_130634.html|script-title=ja:\u9ad8\u5b66\u6b74\u306e\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3000\u82b8\u80fd\u6d3b\u52d5\u3067\u6210\u7e3e\u843d\u3061\u308b\u3068\u3044\u308f\u308c\u305f\u304f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f|date=July 21, 2012|accessdate=August 20, 2017|publisher=Shogakukan Inc|language=Japanese}}</ref> He began music lessons in early childhood, starting with the [[electric organ]] at age three and switching to piano in fourth grade.<ref name=shukanthetv>{{cite magazine |date=November 22, 2016 |script-title=ja:\u9031\u520a\u30b6\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u30b8\u30e7\u30f3 |language=Japanese |page=28 | publisher=Kadokawa Corporation }}</ref> From fourth grade to sixth grade, he played [[trombone]] for his school's brass band.<ref name=shukanthetv /> He also played trumpet and attended cram school.<ref name=shukanthetv /><ref>{{cite book |last=Arashi |date=2005 |script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30e9\u30b7\u30b4\u30c8 : \u307e\u308b\u3054\u3068\u5d50\u306e5\u5e74\u534a |language=Japanese |page=22 | publisher=[[Shueisha]] }}</ref> He joined a local football club after developing a strong interest in football during the [[J.League]] boom in 1993. He wanted to play for a professional team and at one point considered studying abroad in Brazil to become a professional footballer.<ref>{{cite magazine |date=July 8, 2013 |script-title=ja:\u30b6TV\u30b8\u30e7\u30f3COLORS vol.1 RED |language=Japanese |page=11 |publisher=Kadokawa Magazines }}</ref> He played football until his second year of junior high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/20160908/joh16090805040002-n3.html|script-title=ja:\uff12\uff10\u5e74\u30d1\u30e9\u30ea\u30f3\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u3078\u306e\u67b6\u3051\u6a4b\u306b\uff01\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u300c\u8eca\u3044\u3059\u30d0\u30b9\u30b1\u300d\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u306b\u51fa\u6f14|date=September 8, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2017|publisher=Sankei Digital Inc|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, when Sakurai was thirteen years old, he sent an application to the talent agency, Johnny & Associates, and started activities as a [[Johnny's Jr.]].<ref name=newspost7 /> Despite already having an established career with Arashi by the time he graduated from high school, Sakurai went on to attend Keio University, graduating with a [[Bachelor of Economics]] in March 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daily.co.jp/newsflash/gossip/2013/02/11/0005734071.shtml|script-title=ja:\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3000\u6176\u5927\u5408\u683c\u306e\u5f8c\u8f29\u83ca\u6c60\u306b\u52a9\u8a00|date=February 11, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2017|work=Daily Sports|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\n{{For|music-related releases and activities as a member of Arashi|Arashi}}\nSakurai is the designated rapper of Arashi and, although he had written rap lyrics (known to fans as ''Sakurap'') for some of the group's earlier releases under the pen name \"Show\", his first major contribution was for the [[A-side]] song \"[[Hadashi no Mirai/Kotoba Yori Taisetsu na Mono|Kotoba Yori Taisetsu na Mono]]\". While not the first artist from Johnny's to take on rapping, his breakthrough made it easier for his juniors to rap as well, despite being idols.<ref>{{cite episode|title=[[Shounen Club]] Premium|network=[[NHK]]|airdate=June 15, 2008}}</ref> According to [[Taichi Kokubun]] of [[Tokio (band)|Tokio]], ex-[[KAT-TUN]] member {{nihongo|Koki Tanaka|\u7530\u4e2d \u8056|Tanaka K\u014dki}} began to rap because of him.<ref>{{cite episode|title=[[Shounen Club]] Premium|network=[[NHK]]|airdate=January 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe became the first member in Arashi to hold a solo concert called ''The Show'' in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnys-net.jp/j/artists/arashi/bio/bio06.html|title=Arashi Biography 2006|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Johnny & Associates]]|accessdate=October 12, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125204614/http://www.johnnys-net.jp/j/artists/arashi/bio/bio06.html|archive-date=November 25, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sakurai was also a part of a special group with his ''[[Kisarazu Cat's Eye|Kisarazu Cat's Eye World Series]]'' co-stars that same year. Specially formed to promote the movie, they released the movie's theme song {{nihongo|\"Seaside Bye-Bye\"|\u30b7\u30fc\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9\u3070\u3044\u3070\u3044||\"Shisaido Baibai\"}} as a single on October 25, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/confidence/33988/|script-title=ja:\u685c\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u5ca1\u7530\u51c6\u4e00\u30896\u4eba\u304c\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u6728\u66f4\u6d25\u30e6\u30cb\u30c3\u30c8\u3092\u7d50\u6210\uff01\uff01|date=September 7, 2006|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnys-net.jp/j/artists/arashi/disco/_popup/pop_seaside.html|title=\u30b7\u30fc\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9\u3070\u3044\u3070\u3044 (\u6728\u66f4\u6d25\u30ad\u30e3\u30c3\u30c4\u30a2\u30a4 feat. MCU)|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Johnny & Associates|Johnny's net]]|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSakurai co-wrote the lyrics of six songs on the August 2010 Arashi album ''[[Boku no Miteiru F\u016bkei]]''. These songs are \"Movin' On,\" \"Mada Ue o\", \"Taboo\" (Sho Sakurai solo), \"Let Me Down,\" \"Sora Takaku\", and \"Summer Splash!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.johnnys-net.jp/page?id=discoPopup&dataId=1687&target=popup1&lang=en_us|title=\u50d5\u306e\u898b\u3066\u3044\u308b\u98a8\u666f Details|publisher=[[Johnny & Associates|Johnny's net]]|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Acting career ==\n\n=== Drama ===\nUnlike the other members of Arashi who made their major acting debut on stage, Sakurai made his debut on television in Arashi's volleyball-centered short [[Japanese television drama|drama]] {{nihongo|''V no Arashi''|V\u306e\u5d50}} in 1999. In 2001, he took part in his first drama series called {{nihongo|''Tengoku ni Ichiban Chikai Otoko 2''|\u5929\u56fd\u306b\u4e00\u756a\u8fd1\u3044\u7537 \u2013 \u6559\u5e2b\u7de8|The Man Closest to Heaven 2}} with [[Masahiro Matsuoka]] as his teacher. His role as a student with two conflicting characters won him Best Newcomer in the 5th Nikkan Sports Drama Grand Prix Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tbs.co.jp/tengoku/2/cast/profile-ayumi-j.html|title=Official Ayumi T\u014dd\u014d Profile|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]]|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"tengoku_award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/info/Nikkan_Sports_Drama_Grand_Prix|title=Nikkan Sports Drama Grand Prix List|publisher=Tokyograph|accessdate=December 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Sakurai was given his first lead role in the drama {{nihongo|''Yoiko no Mikata''|\u3088\u3044\u5b50\u306e\u5473\u65b9|Ally of Good Children}}. He portrayed {{nihongo|Taiy\u014d Suzuki|\u9234\u6728\u592a\u967d|Suzuki Taiy\u014d}}, a man who strives to prove himself capable of being a nursery school teacher. After ''Yoiko no Mikata'', Sakurai took up many drama specials and mini-dramas until 2005. He even acted in a [[NHK]] late-night drama series called ''Tokio'', in which each episode lasted for fifteen minutes each.\n\nSakurai and bandmate [[Kazunari Ninomiya]] co-starred together in the [[manga]]-based comedy drama ''[[Yamada Tar\u014d Monogatari]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-1046|title=Nino, Sho-kun co-star in comedy series|publisher=Tokyograph|date=May 15, 2007|accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref> Although there was no release of dramas, movies or stageplays from Sakurai in 2008 due to his involvement with the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games in Beijing]] and Arashi's concert tours,<ref name=\"beijing\"/> 2009 saw his first lead role in a drama series since ''Yoiko no Mikata'' in 2003. In the drama ''The Quiz Show 2'' with [[You Yokoyama]], he portrayed an [[amnesia|amnesic]] [[Master of Ceremonies|host]] of a live TV quiz program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-4524|title=Sho Sakurai stars in 'The Quiz Show'|publisher=Tokyograph|date=March 13, 2009|accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref> Sakurai rounded off 2009 with a small guest appearance on the final episode of the drama ''My Girl'', which was bandmate [[Masaki Aiba]]'s first starring role in a serial drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.tvasobi.jp/entries/view/mygirl/8699|script-title=ja:\u6700\u7d42\u56de\uff01 \u5d50\u306e\u30a2\u30ce\u65b9\u304c\u767b\u5834!!|date=December 3, 2009|language=Japanese|publisher=Official My Girl staff blog|accessdate=December 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120708040846/http://blog.tvasobi.jp/entries/view/mygirl/8699|archivedate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2010, Sakurai co-starred with the other members of Arashi in the human suspense drama special ''[[Saigo no Yakusoku]]''. He portrayed {{nihongo|Yukio Tomizawa|\u5bcc\u6fa4\u53cb\u7d00\u592b|Tomizawa Yukio}}, a 28-year-old life insurance salesman who is caught up in a building hijack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/movie/70541/|script-title=ja:\u5d50\u304c10\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u306b\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc5\u4eba\u5168\u54e1\u3067\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u51fa\u6f14\uff01 \u30d5\u30b8\u65b0\u6625\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u300e\u6700\u5f8c\u306e\u7d04\u675f\u300f|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Oricon]]|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=November 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwwz.fujitv.co.jp/fujitv/news/pub_2009/091111varashi.html|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u6625\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u300e\u6700\u5f8c\u306e\u7d04\u675f\u300f|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Fuji Television]] News|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=November 11, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091114043551/http://wwwz.fujitv.co.jp/fujitv/news/pub_2009/091111varashi.html|archivedate=November 14, 2009}}</ref> Sakurai appeared in the [[docudrama]] special {{nihongo|''Kobe Shimbun no Nanokakan''|\u795e\u6238\u65b0\u805e\u306e\uff17\u65e5\u9593|7 Days of the Kobe Newspaper}} on January 16, 2010. He portrayed {{nihongo|Tomohiko Mitsuyama|\u4e09\u6d25\u5c71\u670b\u5f66|Mitsuyama Tomohiko}}, a real photo reporter who worked for the [[Kobe Shimbun]] and helped keep the newspaper running without interruption despite the damage inflicted from the [[Great Hanshin earthquake|Kobe earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kobe-np.co.jp/news/bunka/0002565372.shtml|script-title=ja:\u9707\u707d\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u300c\u795e\u6238\u65b0\u805e\u306e\uff17\u65e5\u9593\u300d\u3000\u653e\u9001\u6642\u9593\u6c7a\u307e\u308b|date=December 7, 2009|language=Japanese|work=[[Kobe Shimbun]]|accessdate=December 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2010, [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]] aired the first episode of Sakurai and [[Maki Horikita]]'s comedy drama {{nihongo|''Tokujo Kabachi!!''|\u7279\u4e0a\u30ab\u30d0\u30c1!!|lit. Extraordinary Quibbling}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-5471|title=Sakurai, Horikita star in \"Tokujo Kabachi\" drama series|publisher=Tokyograph|date=November 21, 2009|accessdate=November 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn August 18, 2011, it was announced that Sakurai would be starring in a Fuji TV drama in the Fall season. The drama {{nihongo|''[[Nazotoki wa Dinner no Ato de]]''|\u8b0e\u89e3\u304d\u306f\u30c7\u30a3\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067|lit. Mystery Solving After Dinner}} is based on a bestselling novel published in 2010 by author Higashigawa Tokuya. Sakurai co-starred with actress [[Keiko Kitagawa]]. The drama aired starting in October.\n\nOn January 25, 2012, [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]] announced a three-night drama special ''Blackboard \u2013 Teachers Waging The Battles of Their Times'', which aired in early April. Sakurai starred on the first night. He played the role of a junior high school teacher who lost his right arm by war and struggled the change of moral after the war. His co-star was be Yuko Ohshima of AKB48.\n\nOn January 26, 2012, it was announced that Fuji TV would produce a drama special for {{nihongo|''[[Nazotoki wa Dinner no Ato de]]''|\u8b0e\u89e3\u304d\u306f\u30c7\u30a3\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067|lit. Mystery Solving After Dinner}} to be aired on March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mantan-web.jp/article/20120126dog00m200015000c.html|title=\u8b0e\u89e3\u304d\u306f\u30c7\u30a3\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067\uff1aSP\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u30673\u6708\u306b\u5fa9\u6d3b\u3000\u5d50\u30fb\u6afb\u4e95\u306e\u6bd2\u820c\u57f7\u4e8b\u304c\u6c96\u7e04\u3067\u30e9\u30d6\u30ed\u30de\u30f3\u30b9|last=|first=|date=January 26, 2012|website=mantan-web.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325093408/https://mantan-web.jp/article/20120126dog00m200015000c.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Sakurai played the lead role of Kageyama again, while actress Keiko Kitagawa reprised her role of Reiko Hosho. The drama special was filmed at Okinawa. A second special<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loca.ash.jp/show/2013/e2013_nazotoki.htm|title=\u8b0e\u89e3\u304d\u306f\u30c7\u30a3\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067SP2 \u30ed\u30b1\u5730\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9|last=|first=|date=2013|website=|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325094855/http://loca.ash.jp/show/2013/e2013_nazotoki.htm|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and a movie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toho.co.jp/movie/lineup/nazotoki/|title=\u6620\u753b \u8b0e\u89e3\u304d\u306f\u30c7\u30a3\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067|last=|first=|date=2013|website=toho.co.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325093647/https://www.toho.co.jp/movie/lineup/nazotoki/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> were released in August 2013\n\n=== Film ===\nIn 2002, Sakurai made his motion picture debut in Arashi's first movie together, {{nihongo|''Pikanchi Life Is Hard Dakedo Happy''|\u30d4\u30ab\u2606\u30f3\u30c1 Life is Hard\u3060\u3051\u3069Happy|Pikanchi Life is Hard But Happy}}. He portrayed Chu, a [[Juvenile delinquency|yankee]] who dropped out of high school after an incident involving his teacher and the girl he had a crush on. That same year, he took on the role of Bambi, a college student who becomes part of a burglar ring at the beckoning of his cancer-stricken friend Bussan to make Bussan's final days worthwhile. In the drama ''[[Kisarazu Cat's Eye]]'' with [[Junichi Okada]] playing the character Bussan, the drama would eventually span into two movie sequels entitled ''Kisarazu Cat's Eye: Nihon Series'' and ''Kisarazu Cat's Eye: World Series'' in 2003 and 2006 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yesasia.com/us/kisarazu-cats-eye-world-series-normal-edition-japan-version/1004636487-0-0-0-en/info.html|title=Kisarazu Cat's Eye World Series (Normal Edition) (Japan Version)|publisher=YesAsia|accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he reprised his role for the sequel of ''Pikanchi Life Is Hard Dakedo Happy'', {{nihongo|''Pikanchi Life Is Hard Dakara Happy''|\u30d4\u30ab\u2606\u2606\u30f3\u30c1 Life is Hard\u3060\u304b\u3089Happy|Pikanchi Life is Hard Therefore Happy}}.\n\nWhile training for a [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] competition with the rest of Arashi on their variety show ''[[Mago Mago Arashi]]'' in 2005, Sakurai filmed for his first starring movie role in the manga-based live-action film ''[[Honey and Clover#Live-action film|Honey and Clover]]''.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Mago Mago Arashi|network=[[Fuji TV]]|airdate=December 3, 2005}}</ref> He portrayed the mellow {{nihongo|Y\u016bta Takemoto|\u7af9\u672c \u7950\u592a|Takemoto Y\u016bta}}.\n\nIn 2007, all the members of Arashi co-starred in their third movie together, {{nihongo|''Kiiroi Namida''|\u9ec4\u8272\u3044\u6d99|Yellow Tears}}, with Sakurai playing the role of an aspiring writer. By the end of the year, it was announced that he would star as Gan-chan in the [[Takashi Miike]] movie ''[[Yatterman (film)|Yatterman]]'', which was not released in theaters until the beginning of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-2130|title=Sho Sakurai to star in \"Yatterman\" movie|publisher=Tokyograph|date=November 25, 2007|accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on June 8, 2010 that Sakurai will co-star with [[Aoi Miyazaki]] in the novel-based movie {{nihongo|''[[Kamisama no Karute]]''|\u795e\u69d8\u306e\u30ab\u30eb\u30c6|God's Medical Records}}, which is scheduled to be released in theaters in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100608/gng1006080505000-n1.htm|script-title=ja:\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u521d\u306e\u533b\u5e2b\u5f79\uff01\u5bae\u5d0e\u3042\u304a\u3044\u3068\u592b\u5a66\u611b (1/2\u30da\u30fc\u30b8)|date=June 8, 2010|language=Japanese|publisher=Sansopo|accessdate=June 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610212016/http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100608/gng1006080505000-n1.htm|archivedate=June 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-6184|title=Sho Sakurai, Aoi Miyazaki star in \"Kamisama no Karute\"|date=June 7, 2010|publisher=Tokyograph|accessdate=June 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2012 the movie version of the popular drama {{nihongo|''[[Nazotoki wa Dinner no Ato de]]''|\u8b0e\u89e3\u304d\u306f\u30c7\u30a3\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067|lit. Mystery Solving After Dinner}} was announced. Sakurai once again portrayed the sharp-tongued butler Kageyama in solving mysteries, co-starring with Kitagawa Keiko. The plot of the movie is a murder case that happens on a luxurious cruise ship. Besides set filming, the production team also filmed overseas in Singapore where they boarded the luxurious cruise ship SuperStar Virgo for onsite filming. The movie completed filming by end of July 2012 and is scheduled for release on August 3, 2013 in Japan.  The International Gala Premiere was held in Singapore on July 27, 2013 at Marina Bay Sands, where about 2,000 fans from Singapore, Thailand and other countries in the region were treated to face-to-face interactions with the main cast of Sakurai and his fellow cast members, Keiko Kitagawa and Shinai Kippei.  Director Masato Hijikata also graced the occasion.  Selected fans got to watch the movie premiere with the cast and director in the Sands Theatre, and were treated to a 20-minute Q&A session with the actors and director after the movie screening.  The Singapore premiere of the movie is scheduled for August 22, 2013, with a special Fans' Screening by Golden Village cinemas on August 14, 2013.\n\n== Other ventures ==\n\n=== Radio ===\nFrom October 5, 2002 to March 30, 2008, Sakurai hosted his own radio show called ''Sho Beat'' on FM Fuji.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnys-net.jp/j/artists/arashi/bio/bio02.html|title=Arashi's 2002 Timeline|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Johnny & Associates]]|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Commercials ===\n{{small|([[:Ja:\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4#CM|\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4#CM]])}}\n* Johnan Academic Preparatory Institute ({{nihongo2|\u57ce\u5357\u4e88\u5099\u6821}}){{small|([[:ja:\u57ce\u5357\u4e88\u5099\u6821|ja]])}} (2005)\n* House Wellness Foods Co., Ltd. ({{nihongo2|\u30cf\u30a6\u30b9\u30a6\u30a7\u30eb\u30cd\u30b9\u30d5\u30fc\u30ba}}){{small|([[:ja:\u30cf\u30a6\u30b9\u30a6\u30a7\u30eb\u30cd\u30b9\u30d5\u30fc\u30ba|ja]])}} \"C1000\" (beverage) (2006-2007)\n* [[Shiseido|Shiseido's]] \"Uno\" brand \"W Design Fiber\" hair product x Kisarazu Cat's Eye collaboration (2006)\n* [[Toyota Financial Services]] Financing Plan {{small|([[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30ca\u30f3\u30b9#\u6b8b\u4fa1\u8a2d\u5b9a\u578b\u30af\u30ec\u30b8\u30c3\u30c8|ja]])}} (2007)\n* [[Cabinet Office (Japan)|Japanese Cabinet Office]] 2050 [[Low-carbon economy]] (2008)\n* [[Japan Post Holdings|Japan Post Co., Ltd.]] New Year's postcard campaign (2008 - 2009), also with Arashi (2019)\n* Able Inc. {{small|([[:ja:\u30a8\u30a4\u30d6\u30eb|ja]])}} real estate company (2008-2011)\n* Asahi Group Holdings, Ltd.\n** [[Asahi Soft Drinks]] \"[[Mitsuya Cider]]\" (2009-2010) In 2020, with Arashi as a group, including a video of himself with audio from [[Satoshi Ohno]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asahiinryo.co.jp/mitsuya-cider/sp/cm/|title=\u300c\u6afb\u4e95\u3055\u3093\u3092\u898b\u3066\u8a9e\u308b\u5927\u91ce\u3055\u3093\u300d\u7de8 15\u79d2|last=|first=|date=March 29, 2020|website=asahiinryo.co.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330062727/https://www.asahiinryo.co.jp/mitsuya-cider/sp/cm/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Asahi Breweries]] \"New Clear Asahi\" beer (2019-)\n* [[Morinaga & Company]] \n** Morinaga Confectionaries and Health Foods Industry\n*** \"in\" (formerly Weider's in) jelly drink  (2015- )\n*** Morinaga Cocoa (2017-)\n** [[Morinaga Milk Industry]] \"pino\" brand ice cream (2010-2016)\n* [[Otsuka Pharmaceutical]] \"[[Oronamin|Oronamin C]]\" drink (2011-2015)\n* [[Aflac|Aflac Japan]] (2011- )\n* [[Ajinomoto|Ajinomoto Frozen Foods]] (2011- )\n* [[Benesse|Benesse Corporation]] Shinkenzemi Junior High School Seminar {{small|([[:ja:\u9032\u7814\u30bc\u30df\u4e2d\u5b66\u8b1b\u5ea7|ja]])}} (2011-2013)\n* JINS Co., Ltd. {{small|([[:ja:\u30b8\u30f3\u30ba|ja]])}} chain stores and shopping centers (2012-2014)\n* [[Kao Corporation]] \n** \"Essential\" hair product {{small|([[:ja:\u30a8\u30c3\u30bb\u30f3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb (\u30b7\u30e3\u30f3\u30d7\u30fc)|ja]])}}  (2014-2016, 2019-)\n** \"MegRhythm\" heat patches and eye masks (2016- )\n* [[Lawson (store)|Lawson Inc.]] (2014-2015)\n* [[Mitsui Fudosan]] real estate (2018- )\n* [[Taisho Pharmaceutical]] \"Claritin EX\" (2020- )<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taisho.co.jp/company/release/2020/2020011701.html|title=\u30a2\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc\u5c02\u7528\u9f3b\u708e\u85ac\u300c\u30af\u30e9\u30ea\u30c1\u30f3\u00ae \uff25\uff38\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u300d\u306eOTC\u533b\u85ac\u54c1\u5206\u985e\u304c\u7b2c1\u985e\u533b\u85ac\u54c1\u3078\u79fb\u884cCM\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u306b\u3001\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3055\u3093\u3092\u8d77\u7528|date=2020-01-17|website=taisho.co.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129021823/https://www.taisho.co.jp/company/release/2020/2020011701.html|archive-date=2020-01-28|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mynavi.jp/article/20200129-962694/|title=\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u9f3b\u708e\u85ac\u65b0CM\u306e\u64ae\u5f71\u306b\u300c\u304b\u306a\u308a\u30b9\u30ea\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u300d \u9699\u9593\u3059\u308a\u629c\u3051\u308b|date=2020-01-29|website=mynavi|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129022034/https://news.mynavi.jp/article/20200129-962694/|archive-date=2020-01-28|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|50F-7LPBdHI|\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3055\u3093\u51fa\u6f14\u3000\u30af\u30e9\u30ea\u30c1\u30f3EX\u3000\uff23\uff2d\u300c\u81ea\u5206\u306b\u5408\u3063\u305f\u9f3b\u708e\u85ac\u300d\u7bc7\u300030\u79d2}}</ref>\n\n=== Variety TV Show ===\n* TBS Ima, ko no kao ga sugoi ! ([[:ja:\u4eca\u3001\u3053\u306e\u9854\u304c\u30b9\u30b4\u3044!|\u4eca\u3001\u3053\u306e\u9854\u304c\u30b9\u30b4\u3044!]]) \u2013 MC (4/11/2013 \u2013 March 20, 2014)\n* TBS Sakurai Ariyoshi The Dangerous Night (\u6afb\u4e95\u6709\u5409\u30a2\u30d6\u30ca\u30a4\u591c\u4f1a) --> Sakurai Ariyoshi The Night (\u6afb\u4e95\u30fb\u6709\u5409 THE\u591c\u4f1a) \u2013 MC (4/17/2014\u2013present)<ref>{{Citation|last=TBS|title=\u6afb\u4e95\u30fb\u6709\u5409THE\u591c\u4f1a|url=http://www.tbs.co.jp/the-yakai/|language=ja-JP|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Newscasts, documentary and informative series ===\nIn 2006, he became a newscaster for the [[Nippon Television|NTV]] news program ''News Zero'' with newscaster {{nihongo|Nobutaka Murao|\u6751\u5c3e \u4fe1\u5c1a|Nobutaka Murao}} and actress [[Mao Kobayashi (actress)|Mao Kobayashi]]. In 2007, he was chosen to help host {{nihongo|''Zero x Senkyo 2007''|Zero\u00d7\u9078\u63192007|Zero x Election 2007}}, a special program which focused the [[2007 Japanese House of Councillors election|2007 House of Councillors elections]]. Sakurai became the first pop idol to host such a program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-1344|title=Sho Sakurai helps bring politics to youths|publisher=Tokyograph|date=July 10, 2007|accessdate=May 7, 2009}}</ref> Following that same year, he was chosen as the main caster for Fuji TV's broadcast of the [[2007 FIVB Women's World Cup|2007 Volleyball World Cup]], marking it the first time in eight years that he has been involved with the Volleyball World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-1827|title=Sho Sakurai appointed as Volleyball World Cup caster|publisher=Tokyograph|date=October 3, 2007|accessdate=May 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Sakurai was a newscaster for the [[2008 FIVB Women's World Olympic Qualification Tournament]] and the main newscaster for the news coverage of the Olympic Games in Beijing on [[Nippon Television|NTV]].<ref name=\"beijing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-2918|title=Sho Sakurai to cover Olympics for NTV|publisher=Tokyograph|date=April 6, 2008|accessdate=May 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fujitv.co.jp/fujitv/news/pub_2008/08-118.html|title=2008\u5317\u4eac\u30aa\u30ea\u30f3\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u30d0\u30ec\u30fc\u30dc\u30fc\u30eb\u4e16\u754c\u6700\u7d42\u4e88\u9078|date=April 25, 2008|publisher=[[Fuji Television]]|accessdate=July 1, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126045605/http://www.fujitv.co.jp/fujitv/news/pub_2008/08-118.html|archivedate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> On June 7, 2009, Sakurai was one of the main newscasters for a special program titled ''Touch! Eco 2009'', which focused on [[environmental issues]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntv.co.jp/ecotv2009/|title=Official Touch Eco Website|accessdate=October 16, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090516210233/http://www.ntv.co.jp/ecotv2009/|archivedate=May 16, 2009}}</ref> On August 30, 2009, he was appointed the official caster for the second part of {{nihongo|''Zero x Senkyo 2009''|Zero\u00d7\u9078\u63192009|Zero x Election 2009}}, which covered Japan's [[2009 Japanese general election|2009 general elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntv.co.jp/zoomin/enta_news/news_167345.html?list=1&count=1|title=Sho Sakurai to be Election Navigator|language=Japanese|publisher=Zoom in Super|date=August 1, 2009|accessdate=September 2, 2009}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nSakurai was the special newscaster for the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] news coverage on NTV with [[Shizuka Arakawa]] as the main newscaster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100111/gng1001110505000-n1.htm |script-title=ja:\u6afb\u4e95\uff06\u8352\u5ddd\u3001\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\u30d0\u30f3\u30af\u30fc\u30d0\u30fc\u4e94\u8f2a\u306e\u9854\uff01 |date=January 11, 2010 |language=Japanese |publisher=Sanspo |accessdate=January 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113043216/http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100111/gng1001110505000-n1.htm |archivedate=January 13, 2010 }}</ref> On July 11, 2010, he took on the role of a navigator for the second half of {{nihongo|''Zero x Senkyo 2010''|Zero\u00d7\u9078\u63192010|Zero x Election 2010}}, which focused on the [[2010 Japanese House of Councillors election|2010 House of Councillors elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100701/gnj1007010502007-n1.htm|script-title=ja:\u9078\u6319\u7279\u756a\u3000\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\u306f\u7d33\u52a9\u3001\uff34\uff22\uff33\u306f\u305f\u3051\u3057|date=July 1, 2010|language=Japanese|publisher=Sanspo|accessdate=July 1, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703150248/http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100701/gnj1007010502007-n1.htm|archivedate=July 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2010, Sakurai traveled to Romania, Germany, and Russia to do a special report on world poverty for 24-Hour Television, which was broadcast on August 29, 2010. He interviewed former Soviet Union General Secretary and [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winner [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] about nuclear disarmament and poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hochi.yomiuri.co.jp/entertainment/news/20100821-OHT1T00020.htm|script-title=ja:\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u30b4\u30eb\u30d0\u30c1\u30e7\u30d5\u6c0f\u3068\u300c\u8ca7\u56f0\u300d\u300c\u6838\u8ecd\u7e2e\u300d\u6fc0\u8ad6\uff13\uff10\u5206|date=August 21, 2010|language=Japanese|work=[[Sports Hochi]]|accessdate=January 22, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825021551/http://hochi.yomiuri.co.jp/entertainment/news/20100821-OHT1T00020.htm|archivedate=August 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSakurai was chosen by Nippon Television Network (NTV) of Japan as the main MC of their royal wedding special, \"British Royal Family Prince William and Princess Kate\". The special was aired on April 29, 2011, featuring video footage from the British Broadcasting Channel that covered the joyous occasion for the British royal family.\n\nSakurai co-hosted the special program \u5fa9\u8208\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3_\u307f\u3093\u306a\u306e\u30c1\u30ab\u30e9 aired on March 11, 2012, a special program to remember the 9.0 magnitude earthquake that hit North-eastern Japan in 2011.\n\nOn May 13, 2012, NTV of Japan announced the appointment of Sakurai as the main caster for their [[2012 London Summer Olympics]] coverages. It is Sakurai's third consecutive Olympic main caster appointment for NTV after 2008 Beijing and 2010 Vancouver. 2012 London Olympics runs from July 27 to August 12, 2012.\n\nOn August 4, 2015 Sakurai and [[Akira Ikegami]] hosted the first episode of an NTV series called {{nihongo|''Sakurai Sh\u014d & Ikegami Akira Ky\u014dkasho de manabenai''|\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4&\u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70 \u6559\u79d1\u66f8\u3067\u5b66\u3079\u306a\u3044|Sho Sakurai & Akira Ikegami Can't Learn with Textbooks}} {{small|([[:ja:\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u00d7\u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70 \u6559\u79d1\u66f8\u3067\u5b66\u3079\u306a\u3044SP|ja]])}}. This first installment dealt with a look at the war 70 years after Japan's surrender, and the Japanese peoples understanding of it. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japanesestudies.org.uk/ejcjs/vol16/iss1/mandujano-salazar.html|title=The war that cannot be learned from textbooks or the national identity discourse that can be perceived in media?: The war that can be learned from television|last=Mandujano-Salazar|first=Yunuen Ysela|date=April 30, 2016|website=japanesestudies.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406040236/https://www.japanesestudies.org.uk/ejcjs/vol16/iss1/mandujano-salazar.html|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A second episode aired on March 1, 2016. This one dealt with a historical look of the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|Great Eastern Japan Earthquake]] 5 years after, primarily, and other disasters around the world such as eruptions, landslides, floods and typhoons, and how to deal with them and prepare in order to save lives. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dogatch.jp/news/ntv/37527/detail/|title=\u5d50\u30fb\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u304c\u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70\u3068\u518d\u30bf\u30c3\u30b0\u3001\u7fbd\u751f\u7d50\u5f26\u3082\u601d\u3044\u8a9e\u308b \u9707\u707d\u304b\u30895\u5e74\u76ee\u306e\u7279\u5225\u756a\u7d44|last=|first=|date=February 3, 2016|website=dogatch.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406041314/https://dogatch.jp/news/ntv/37527/detail/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A new episode aired two years later, February 6, 2018. On this one, Sakurai and Ikegami talked about \"Unexpected Japan\", dealing with politics and it's relationship to the [[Olympic Games]], [[North Korea]] and the [[Imperial House of Japan|Imperial Family]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetv.jp/news/detail/134002/|title=\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\uff06\u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70\u30bf\u30c3\u30b02\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u306b\u5fa9\u6d3b\uff01 \u6c60\u4e0a\u306e\u8a00\u8449\u306b\u6afb\u4e95\u300c\u6065\u305a\u304b\u3057\u3044(\u7b11)\u300d|last=|first=|date=January 15, 2018|website=thetv.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406041401/https://thetv.jp/news/detail/134002/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/entame/883510/|title=\u5d50\u30fb\u6afb\u4e95  \u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70\u6c0f\u3068\u518d\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\uff11\uff10\u5e74\u5f8c\u898b\u636e\u3048\u56f2\u3044\u8fbc\u307f|last=|first=|date=January 12, 2018|website=|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406040154/https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/entame/883510/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A fourth installment of the series is set to air on May 4, 2020, where they will talk about the \"ultra difficult problems\" facing Japan, like the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]] and all that has happened around the [[pandemic]], such as the closing of schools, delays in services and postponement of big events, like the [[2020 Summer Olympics|Tokyo Olympics]] and [[2020 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mynavi.jp/article/20200406-1011532/|title=\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\uff06\u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70\uff1a\u300c\u6559\u79d1\u66f8\u3067\u5b66\u3079\u306a\u3044\u300d\u7b2c4\u5f3e\u304cGW\u653e\u9001\u3000\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u3001\u4e94\u2026|last=|first=|date=April 6, 2020|website=news.mynavi.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406041450/https://news.mynavi.jp/article/20200406-1011532/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2159184/full/|title=\u6afb\u4e95\u7fd4\u3001\u6c60\u4e0a\u5f70\u3068\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u201c\u8d85\u96e3\u554f\u201d\u306b\u6311\u3080 \u300e\u6559\u79d1\u66f8\u3067\u5b66\u3079\u306a\u3044\u300f\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u7b2c4\u5f3e\u304c\u653e\u9001\u6c7a\u5b9a|last=|first=|date=April 6, 2020|website=oricon.co.jp|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406042605/https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2159184/full/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Music Event ===\n* Nippon TV Best Artist ([[:ja:\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\u7cfb\u97f3\u697d\u306e\u796d\u5178 \u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8|\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\u7cfb\u97f3\u697d\u306e\u796d\u5178 \u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8]]) Main Host (2009\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tokyohive.com/article/2019/11/sakurai-sho-to-be-the-host-for-best-artist-for-the-11th-consecutive-time|title=Sakurai Sho to be the host for 'Best Artist' for the 11th consecutive time|publisher=tokyohive.com|date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213132926/https://www.tokyohive.com/article/2019/11/sakurai-sho-to-be-the-host-for-best-artist-for-the-11th-consecutive-time|archive-date=December 13, 2019|access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntv.co.jp/best-artist/|script-title=ja:\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c82019\uff5c\u65e5\u672c\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3|year=2019|website=ntv.co.jp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213134618/https://www.ntv.co.jp/best-artist/|archive-date=December 13, 2019|access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* Nippon TV Music Festival \u2013 The Power of Music ([[:ja:THE MUSIC DAY|\u65e5\u30c6\u30ec\u7cfb\u97f3\u697d\u306e\u796d\u5178 \u97f3\u697d\u306e\u3061\u304b\u30892012]]) Main Host (2012) \n* Nippon TV [[:ja:THE MUSIC DAY|The Music Day]] Main Host (2013\u20132017)\n* NHK [[K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen#Results|K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen]] White team host (solo, 2018, 2019), (as part of [[Arashi]], 2010 \u2013 2014)\n\n===Telethon===\nSakurai appears as main personality in [[Nippon TV|NTV]]'s 24-Hr TV for 6th time, 5 with [[Arashi]] (2004, 2008, 2012, 2013, 2019) ([[:ja:24\u6642\u9593\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3 \u300c\u611b\u306f\u5730\u7403\u3092\u6551\u3046\u300d#\u5404\u56de\u306e\u653e\u9001\u6982\u8981|24\u6642\u9593\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tokyohive.com/article/2019/03/arashi-to-host-this-years-24-hour-television|website=tokyohive.com|date=March 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213154527/https://www.tokyohive.com/article/2019/03/arashi-to-host-this-years-24-hour-television|title=Arashi to host this year's '24-Hour Television'|archive-date=December 13, 2019|access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref> and 1 by himself (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aramajapan.com/news/tvmovie/sakurai-sho-kamenashi-kazuya-koyama-keiichiro-are-this-years-24-hr-tv-main-personalities/73878/|title=Sakurai Sho, Kamenashi Kazuya & Koyama Keiichiro are this year's \"24-HR TV\" main personalities|website=ARAMA! JAPAN|date=April 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213154405/https://aramajapan.com/news/tvmovie/sakurai-sho-kamenashi-kazuya-koyama-keiichiro-are-this-years-24-hr-tv-main-personalities/73878/|archive-date=December 13, 2019|access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Contributions ==\n\n=== Rap lyrics ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ A-side songs\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| 2003\n| \"[[Hadashi no Mirai/Kotoba Yori Taisetsu na Mono|Kotoba Yori Taisetsu na Mono]]\" \n|-\n| 2004\n| \"[[Pikanchi Double]]\"<br />\n|-\n| 2005\n| \"[[Sakura Sake]]\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| \"[[Kitto Daij\u014dbu]]\"\n|-\n| 2007 \n| \"[[We Can Make It!]]\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"[[Step and Go]]\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"[[Truth/Kaze no Muk\u014d e|Kaze no Muk\u014d e]]\"\n|-\n| 2009\n| \"[[Believe/Kumorinochi, Kaisei|Believe]]\"\n|-\n| 2012\n| \"[[Face Do